I do the same exact thing...I'm getting better with it on my current
meds.  If I say something stupid to someone and they get a little
upset, I'll dwell on it seemingly forever.  You definitely seem to
have signs of OCD.  There are different manifestations of OCD.  You
don't have to be someone who goes through a ritual of washing hands
for an hour,etc. to be dx'ed with OCD.  Like I said in my post.  I do
have some compulsions, but the &quot;O&quot; part, obsessive thinking is my
major problem.  BTW, I get up and down at least 5 times before being
able to watch a movie too.
</POST>
<POST>
<POSTER> Matt &lt;matcho...@verizon.net&gt; </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2007-07-15T11:57:00 </POSTDATE>
<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; I know quite a few people who are considered to be &quot;normal&quot;, but tend to
&gt; show some obsessive(-compulsive) behaviour. Doesn't have to mean they've
&gt; got OCD. For instance, lots of people doublecheck to see if they've
&gt; locked their car, front door, ... (and then sometimes check it again).
">

Yeah.  Though I don't think of it as ocd behaviour.  It's more like
being thoughtful and careful.  It's when you have to check it 10
times...and if you don't, you're veins will crawl and you'll want to
explode because of the anxiety.  Many people are very anal and
organized (another OCD trait), but it's when it interferes with the
normal functioning of your life that there's a problem.  OCD is
considered and anxiety disorder, and is common to co-exist with
bipolar.  I actually just came across an article that stated &quot;...These
bipolar OCD patients had a significantly lower rate of checking
rituals&quot;.  That reminds me of my mental disorder.
</POST>
